[[File:Kolmen valtakunnan rajapyykki 27.4.1945.png|thumb|upright=1.75|Finnish soldiers raise the war flag at the three-country cairn between Norway, Sweden, and Finland on 27 April 1945, the end of World War II in Finland]]
'''''Raising the Flag on the Three-Country Cairn'''''{{refn|Colonel Oinonen originally titled the picture as "[a] scene at the three-country boundary stone on 27 April 1945" ({{lang-fi|Kohtaus kolmen valtakunnan rajakivellä 27.4.1945}}; original photograph scan received from the Military Museum of Finland), but it is usually labelled as "Finnish soldiers raising the flag on the three-country cairn" ({{lang-fi|Suomalaissotilaat nostavat lipun kolmen valtakunnan rajapyykille}}) or a similar variation.<ref name="Yle"/><ref name="SK"/><ref name="IS"/><ref name="ESS"/>|group="Note"}} is a historic photograph taken on 27 April 1945, which was the last day of the [[Military history of Finland during World War II|Second World War in Finland]]. It depicts a [[Finnish Army]] patrol of Battle Group Loimu, Infantry Regiment 1 ({{Lang-fi|taisteluosasto Loimu, jalkaväkirykmentti 1}}), raising the [[Flag of Finland|Finnish flag]] on the [[Three-Country Cairn|three-country cairn]] between [[Norway]], [[Sweden]], and [[Finland]] to celebrate the last German troops withdrawing from Finland. The photograph was taken by the commander of Infantry Regiment 1, Colonel [[Väinö Oinonen]] (alternatively V.J. Oinonen). It became a widely circulated symbol of World War II in Finland.

== Background ==
[[File:Flag_at_Kilpisjärvi_1945.jpg|left|thumb|
The small Finnish flag raised first on the cairn on 26 April 1945
]]
Amidst World War II, Finland fought both the [[Winter War]] of 1939–1940 and [[Continuation War]] of 1941–1944 against the Soviet Union. During the latter, Finland cooperated with [[Nazi Germany]], which had the 200,000-strong [[20th Mountain Army (Wehrmacht)|20th Mountain Army]] led by {{Lang|de|Generaloberst}} [[Lothar Rendulic]] stationed in [[Finnish Lapland]]. On September 1944, Finland agreed to a separate peace with the Soviet Union; a peace which required that Finland disarm or expel any German soldiers from Finland. The demand led to the [[Lapland War]]; the 20th Mountain Army started withdrawing north towards [[German occupation of Norway|occupied Norway]] with the [[Finnish Army]]'s [[Finnish III Corps (Continuation War)|III Corps]], led by General [[Hjalmar Siilasvuo]], in pursuit. By November, the war came to an effective end when most German units had withdrawn to Norway and the [[Lyngen]] Line—although some entrenched German forces still remained in Finland at [[Kilpisjärvi]] in the corridor leading to the border tripoint between Norway, Sweden, and Finland.{{refn|The corridor is nationally called Arm's Lapland ({{lang-fi|Käsivarren Lappi}}) or the Finnish Arm ({{lang-sv|Finska armen}}).|group="Note"}}{{sfn|Jowett|Snodgrass|2012}}{{sfn|Nenye|Munter|Wirtanen|Birks|2016|loc=Chpt. 3}}

On 25 April 1945, after it was determined that the final German formations in Finnish territory were withdrawing, a 60-strong battle patrol led by Captain Valkonen was assigned to recon if Finnish Lapland was free from ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' forces. The detachment was assembled from 1st Company, Battle Group Loimu, Infantry Regiment 1, and departed on its mission at 13.00 pm the same day from southern Kilpisjärvi. The ski patrol advanced north-west towards Norway for around {{Convert|8|km|mi|abbr=on}} until it was split in two near the [[Saana]] fell. The smaller group would approach the Norwegian border along the road while the bulk of the patrol would continue with Captain Valkonen towards the three-country cairn farther off. They reached the cairn by 1:15 am on 26 April after skiing approximately {{Convert|10|km|mi|abbr=on}} more. [[Pioneer (military)|Pioneer]] Antti Poikola attached a small [[flag of Finland]] to the cairn and the patrol reported back by radio that no Germans had been sighted on Finnish soil. Valkonen and his team shot three gun salutes at the cairn before leaving; the shots rang out across the [[fell]]<nowiki/>s and startled a Swedish border guard unit nearby.{{sfn|Kulju|2017|loc=Chpt. 4}}{{sfn|Oilinki|1998|loc=Chpt. Kun Poikolan Antti lopetti Lapin sodan}}

Around the noon of 26 April, commander of the battalion, Major Martti Santavuori and a mixed Finnish–Swedish patrol arrived at the tripoint. A German {{Lang|de|Gebirgsjäger}} unit approached them from Norway, and, with knowledge that they would not engage the Swedes, Major Santavuori signaled the German leader to meet up at the border. An Austrian {{Lang|de|Feldwebel}} soon skied closer and they discussed the war, both past and future. Major Santavuori and the {{Lang|de|Feldwebel}} saluted, shook hands and bid each other "as good a future as fate has to offer" before parting ways.{{sfn|Kulju|2017|loc=Chpt. 4}}

== Flag-raising ==
{{Location map|Scandinavia|width=|float=right|caption=Location of the tripoint depicted in the photograph in Northern Europe|label=|marksize=10|lat_deg=69.059972|lon_deg=20.548639}}On 27 April, commander of Infantry Regiment 1, Colonel [[Väinö Oinonen]] (alternatively V.J. Oinonen), arrived at the cairn to inspect the situation with a detachment of soldiers including photography specialists, a larger flag, and a better flagpole. The war flag of Finland was ceremoniously raised on the cairn and Colonel Oinonen took the titular photo—with the {{convert|894|m|ft|abbr=on}}-high Golddabakti fell of Norway in the background.{{sfn|Kulju|2017|loc=Chpt. 4}}{{sfn|Oilinki|1998|loc=Chpt. Kun Poikolan Antti lopetti Lapin sodan}} Amidst the festivities, a shout of "{{Lang|de|Wer da}}?!" surprised the Finnish soldiers. Even though the area had been inspected, a German unit lay waiting in position on the Norwegian side of the border. The flag-raising soldiers took cover behind the cairn. Battle was avoided after a Swedish officer approached to act as an intermediary. Soon after, Colonel Oinonen resolved the situation with two {{Lang|de|Oberleutnante}}, who shared German Juno cigarettes with him. The officers saluted each other and went their ways; the time was 13:30 pm. On 28 April, General Siilasvuo sent a telegram to Finnish Commander-in-Chief [[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim|C.G.E. Mannerheim]], reporting that the {{Lang|de|Wehrmacht}} had been expelled from Northern Finland.{{sfn|Kulju|2017|loc=Chpt. 4}}

== Aftermath ==

The picture became widely circulated in Finland and was an example of an iconic [[War photography|war photograph]] in Finnish World War II history. It was compared to similar pictures, such as the American ''[[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima]]'' and the Soviet ''[[Raising a Flag over the Reichstag]]'', although it was not considered to have become as symbolic as they were. In fact, the Finnish popular memory of the conflict relied equally on fictional pictures, such as the cover of ''[[The Unknown Soldier (novel)|The Unknown Soldier]]'', a 1954 war novel about the [[Continuation War]].<ref name="Yle">{{Cite web|url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9927243|title=Sotilaiden omat kamerat taltioivat Suomen sodista todellisuuden, joka ei kelvannut virallisiin kuviin – tutkija: "Hyvin rajua huumoria"|last=Mäntymäki|first=Varpu|date=2017-11-19|website=Yle Uutiset|language=fi|trans-title=Soldiers' own cameras captured the reality of Finland's wars, which wasn't approved for official photographs – researcher: "Very rough humour"|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119092018/https://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9927243|archivedate=19 November 2017|deadurl=no|access-date=2018-02-28|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="IS">{{Cite news|url=https://www.is.fi/kotimaa/art-2000000916473.html|title=Tämä ikoninen sotakuva on kuin suomalainen versio Iwo Jiman lipun pystytyksestä|last=Juuti|first=Mikko|date=2015-04-27|work=Ilta-Sanomat|access-date=2018-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302150051/https://www.is.fi/kotimaa/art-2000000916473.html|archive-date=2 March 2018|dead-url=no|language=fi-FI|trans-title=This iconic war photograph is like the Finnish version of raising the flag on Iwo Jima|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="SK">{{Cite journal|last=Lindstendt|first=Risto|last2=Kleemola|first2=Olli|date=2011-12-02|title=Tuntematon ikoni|trans-title=Unknown icon|url=|deadurl=no|journal=[[Suomen Kuvalehti]]|language=fi|volume=|issue=48|pages=48–57|archiveurl=|archivedate=2 March 2018|access-date=|via=|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="ESS">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ess.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/art2364591|title=Lasten ristiretki päätti Suomen sotatien Lapissa 27. huhtikuuta 1945|last=Vainonen|first=Joel M.|date=2017-04-27|work=Etelä-Suomen Sanomat|access-date=2018-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504222749/http://www.ess.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/art2364591|archive-date=4 May 2017|dead-url=no|language=fi-FI|trans-title=The children's crusade concluded the Finnish war effort in Lapland on 27 April 1945|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Oilinki|1998|loc=Chpt. Kun Poikolan Antti lopetti Lapin sodan}}

