[[Ernő Dohnányi]] completed his first symphony, unnumbered and entitled '''Symphony in F''', in 1896,<ref name="grymes2001">on May 17. See {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ah2d3pc2dqQC&pg=PA41|author=Grymes|first=James A.|year=2001|title=Ernst von Dohnányi : a bio-bibliography|location=Westport, Conn.|publisher=Greenwood Press|page=41|series=Bio-bibliographies in music|volume=86|type=e-Book|ISBN=0-313-07440-2|accessdate=February 19, 2013}} Cited in VIAF. Appears as W111 in the listing.</ref> while a student of [[Hans von Koessler]]. It was never formally published, and although awarded the Hungarian King's Prize,{{sfn|Grymes|2005|p=4}} it did not achieve significant critical acclaim. The work, like many of Dohnányi's early compositions, bears the imprint of [[Johannes Brahms]], who had championed the young composer after hearing a performance of Dohnányi's ''Piano Quintet No. 1''. The ''Symphony in F'' was given moderate attention after being recorded in 2011. It is approximately thirty minutes in length.
It requires 2 flutes, 2 oboes, 2 clarinets, 2 bassoons, 4 horns, 3 trumpets, 3 trombones, tuba, timpani and strings<ref name="grymes2001"/> and while not published in his lifetime, exists in sketches and score at the [[National Széchényi Library]], Budapest.<ref name="grymes2001"/> It was premiered 2 June 1897, in Budapest with Gyula Erkel (son of [[Ferenc Erkel|Ferenc]]) conducting.<ref name="grymes2001"/>
==Form== Dohnányi wrote the work in the traditional four-movement symphonic format. He marks the score with the following:
#Allegro #Adagio #Scherzo – Prestissimo #Andante
==Recording== In 2011, the symphony's premiere recording (and only recording to date) was conducted by László Kovács.<ref>László Kovács (with the Miskolc Symphony Orchestra), recorded and released in 2011 on ''Ernő Dohnányi (1877-1960): Symphony in F, Zrínyi Overture, Op. 2, Suite en valse, Op. 39'' ([[Hungaroton|Hungaroton Records Publisher Ltd]]) as "Dohnányi: Symphony in F" (29:34)</ref>
