{{use British English|date=February 2015}} {{infobox artwork | image_file=Paul Gauguin, Nafea Faa Ipoipo? 1892, oil on canvas, 101 x 77 cm.jpg | image_size=250px | title=When Will You Marry? | other_language_1=Tahitian | other_title_1=Nafea faa ipoipo? | artist=[[Paul Gauguin]] | year=1892 | medium=[[Oil on canvas]] | city= | dimensions = {{convert|101|x|77|cm|in}} | museum=Private collection }}
'''''When Will You Marry?''''' ({{lang-fr|Quand te maries-tu ?}}, {{lang-ty|Nafea faa ipoipo}}) is an oil painting from 1892 by the French [[Post-Impressionist]] artist [[Paul Gauguin]]. On loan to the [[Kunstmuseum Basel|Kunstmuseum]] in [[Basel]], Switzerland for nearly a half-century, it was sold privately by the family of [[Rudolf Staechelin]] to [[Al-Mayassa bint Hamad bin Khalifa Al-Thani|Sheikha Al-Mayassa bint Hamad Al-Thani]], in February 2015 for close to US $210 million (£155 million), [[List of most expensive paintings|one of the highest prices ever paid for a work of art]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/06/arts/design/gauguin-painting-is-said-to-fetch-nearly-300-million.html|title=Gauguin Painting Is Said to Fetch Nearly $300 Million|last1=Reyburn|first1=Scott|last2=Carvajal|first2=Doreen|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 5, 2015|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name="BBC">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-31183733 |title=Gauguin painting breaks sale record at nearly $300m |accessdate=7 February 2015 |publisher=BBC News |date=7 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cascone|first1=Sarah|title=Does Qatar's $300 Million Paul Gauguin Acquisition Hide A Dark Secret?|url=http://news.artnet.com/market/does-qatars-300-million-paul-gauguin-acquisition-hide-a-dark-secret-246607|website=news.artnet.com|publisher=[[artnet]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WE1EuSmB|archivedate=10 February 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> The painting was on exhibition at the [[Beyeler Foundation|Fondation Beyeler]], [[Riehen]], until 28 June 2015.<ref name="Huffington Post">{{cite news|title=Paul Gauguin at Fondation Beyeler|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/vernissagetv/paul-gauguin-at-fondation_b_6640578.html|website=huffingtonpost.com|publisher=[[Huffington Post]]|date=8 February 2015}}</ref>
==History== Gauguin travelled to [[Tahiti]] for the first time in 1891. His hope was to find "an edenic paradise where he could create pure, [[tribal art|'primitive' art]]",<ref name="GI">{{cite web | url=http://www.galleryintell.com/artex/nafea-fas-ipoipo-will-marry-paul-gauguin/ | title=Nafea fas ipoipo (When will you marry) by Paul Gauguin | work=galleryIntell | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> rather than the [[primitivism|primitivist]] faux works being turned out by painters in [[France]]. Upon arrival, he found that Tahiti was not as he imagined it: it had been colonised in the 18th century, and at least two-thirds of the indigenous people of the island had been killed by diseases brought by Europeans.<ref name="Graves">{{cite web|last1=Graves|first1=Jen|title=You May Be Infected Already|url=http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/you-may-be-infected-already/Content?oid=12587203|website=thestranger.com|publisher=[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WCGlQDkJ|archivedate=8 February 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> "Primitive" culture had been wiped out. Despite this, he painted many pictures of native women: nude, dressed in traditional Tahitian clothes, and dressed in Western-style dresses, as is the rear figure in ''When Will You Marry?''.
[[File:Gauguin - Kauerndes Mädchen von Tahiti - 1892.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Full-scale working study, charcoal and pastel, [[Art Institute of Chicago]]]]
The front and middle ground are built up in areas of green, yellow and blue. A traditionally dressed young woman has settled on the threshold between the front and middle ground. Richard Field suggests the white ''[[tiare]]'' flower behind her left ear indicates she is seeking a husband.<ref name = Field>Field pp. 132-41</ref><ref name= Stuckey>Stuckey pp. 263-64</ref><ref name= Maurer>Maurer {{Google books|wf_PoXKhggkC|title=The Pursuit of Spiritual Wisdom: The Thought and Art of Vincent van Gogh and Paul Gauguin|page=147|plainurl=}}</ref>{{efn|The custom is alluded to in a 1914 letter from [[Rupert Brooke]] to [[Cathleen Nesbitt]]. According to Brooke, the flower worn at the left ear meant the wearer had found a sweetheart. Brooke spent some months in the South Seas 1913-14 and took a native lover in Tahiti.<ref name="Potter">{{cite web|last1=Potter|first1=Caroline|title=This Side of Paradise: Rupert Brooke and the South Seas|url=http://asketchofthepast.com/2014/08/08/this-side-of-paradise-rupert-brooke-and-the-south-seas/|website=asketchofthepast.com|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WEsBYLnl|archivedate=10 February 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref>}} Behind her a second figure in a high-necked Western-style dress sits erectly. Field thought her gesture derives from Buddhist art.<ref name = Field/> Naomi E. Maurer subsequently identified it as a ''[[mudra]]'' denoting threatening or warning.<ref name= "Maurer"/> The front woman stretches herself, her facial features stylized and simplified. Field thought her pose had a Japanese precedent, Charles F. Stuckey suggests Delacroix's ''[[Women of Algiers]]''.<ref name= Stuckey/>{{efn|Stuckey says Gauguin was evidently fascinated by the pose and, beside the full-scale working drawing, incorporated it in ''Where Are You Going?'' (W 478 and W 501), two watercolors, an oil sketch (W 445) as well as a sketchbook study.
<gallery widths="150px" heights="150px" perrow="5"> Paul Gauguin - Fragments of bodies, a decorative design and two crouching Tahitian women in a landscape related to Nafea Faaipoipo (When Will You Marry) - NGA 2002.233V.jpg | Pencil sketch, 1892, [[Art Institute of Chicago]] Paul Gauguin - Two Tahitian Women in a Landscape - NGA 1922.4795.jpg|''Two Tahitian Women in a Landscape'', ''circa'' 1892, [[Art Institute of Chicago]] Gauguin - Tahitische Szene.jpg|''Tahitian Scene'', ''circa'' 1892, [[Thielska Galleriet]] Paul Gauguin - Black Pigs with Crouching Tahitian W455.jpg | ''Black Pigs with Crouching Tahitian'' (W 445), 1891, [[Private collection]] Paul Gauguin 128.jpg|''Where Are You Going?'', 1893, [[Hermitage Museum]] </gallery>
}} The rear female figure is flush with the yellow-blue area. Her face is painted with individual features and represents the centre of the image. The pink colour of her dress is clearly distinct from the other colours. At the bottom right is the inscription "NAFEA Faa ipoipo" (''When will you marry''). Gauguin commonly inscribed his paintings in [[Tahitian language|Tahitian]] at this time: he was fascinated by the language, though never advanced beyond its rudiments.<ref name= "Maurer"/>
Art historian [[Nancy Mowll Mathews]] wrote that Gauguin "portrayed the [Tahitian] natives as living only to sing and to make love. That's how he got the money from his friends and raised the public's interest in his adventure. But, of course, he knew the truth, which was that Tahiti was an unremarkable island with an international, westernised community".<ref name="7feb3">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/feb/07/paul-gauguins-when-will-you-marry-becomes-most-expensive-artwork-ever | title=Paul Gauguin's When Will You Marry? becomes most expensive artwork ever | work=The Guardian | date=7 February 2015 | accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> These paintings of Tahitians, including ''When Will You Marry?'', were met with relative indifference when Gauguin returned to France, his 1893 [[Durand-Ruel]] exhibition only a limited success generating some favourable reviews but little by way of sales. Gauguin placed this painting on [[consignment]] at the exhibition at a price of 1,500 francs, the highest price he assigned and shared by only one other painting, but had no takers.<ref name= Stuckey/> Staechelin eventually purchased it at the ''Maison Moos'' gallery in Geneva in 1917.
A pencil sketch of the painting's central figure was uncovered and authenticated in a 2017 episode of ''[[Fake or Fortune?]]''<ref>[https://www.antiquestradegazette.com/news/2017/gauguin-sketch-dismissed-as-a-fake-is-valued-at-200-000-after-fake-or-fortune-investigation/ Gauguin sketch dismissed as a fake is valued at £200,000 after ''Fake or Fortune?'' investigation], ''Antiques Trade Gazette''</ref> {{Clear}}
